.TH BRANCHIFY 1 "July 2026" "branchify 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
branchify \- convert an arbitrary string into a valid git branch name
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B branchify
.RI [ STRING ...]
.br
.B echo
.RI STRING
.B |
.B branchify
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B branchify
converts free-form text (a commit message, ticket title, or any string)
into a branch name that is guaranteed to pass
.BR "git check-ref-format --branch" .
.PP
It lowercases the input, replaces whitespace and underscores with hyphens,
strips characters git rejects in refs, collapses redundant separators, and
trims the result to a sane length.
.PP
Input can be given as command-line arguments (joined with spaces) or piped
in on standard input.
.SH RULES ENFORCED
.TP
.B lowercase
All characters are lowercased.
.TP
.B separators
Spaces and underscores become hyphens; slashes are preserved as path
separators (e.g. for scoped names like
.IR feature/foo ).
.TP
.B disallowed characters
The characters
.BR "~ ^ : ? * [ \e"
and ASCII control characters are stripped, as are any other characters
outside
.IR "[a-z0-9._/-]" .
.TP
.B dots and slashes
Consecutive dots
.RI ( .. )
and consecutive slashes are collapsed to a single separator.
.TP
.B leading/trailing separators
Leading or trailing
.IR . ", " / ", " -
are stripped.
.TP
.B reserved sequences
A trailing
.I .lock
suffix and any
.I @{
sequence are removed; a bare
.I @
is replaced with the literal string
.IR branch .
.TP
.B length
The result is truncated to 100 characters.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.B 0
on success. The script has no failure modes for normal input; an empty or
fully-stripped result falls back to the literal branch name
.IR branch .
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B branchify "Fix bug: user login fails!!"
.RI \(-> " fix-bug-user-login-fails"
.TP
.B branchify "Add OAuth2 support (v2)"
.RI \(-> " add-oauth2-support-v2"
.TP
.B echo "Some Title" | branchify
.RI \(-> " some-title"
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR git-check-ref-format (1),
.BR git-branch (1)
.SH AUTHOR
Generated for local use; not a distributed package.
